  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some bad habits that self-taught programmers develop?",
  "response": "Self-taught programmers can develop several bad habits that may hinder their growth, efficiency, or the quality of their work. Here are some common ones:\n\n1. **Lack of Fundamentals**: Skipping over core concepts such as data structures, algorithms, or software design principles in favor of quickly learning specific languages or frameworks.\n\n2. **Copy-Pasting Code**: Relying heavily on copy-pasting code from the internet without fully understanding it, which can lead to a lack of problem-solving skills.\n\n3. **Poor Code Organization**: Writing code without proper structure, leading to hard-to-read and maintainable code. This might include not following conventions for file organization, naming, or formatting.\n\n4. **Ignoring Version Control**: Not using version control systems like Git, or not using them effectively, which can lead to issues with collaboration and code management.\n\n5. **Neglecting Documentation**: Failing to document code or write comments, making it difficult for others (or themselves later) to understand the purpose and functionality of the code.\n\n6. **Overengineering**: Creating overly complex solutions for simple problems, which can make the codebase unwieldy and difficult to maintain.\n\n7. **Avoiding Testing**: Not writing tests or practicing test-driven development, which can lead to fragile codebases that are hard to trust.\n\n8. **Not Seeking Feedback**: Avoiding code reviews or input from more experienced developers, missing out on learning opportunities and best practices.\n\n9. **Focusing on \"Knowing\" Instead of \"Doing\"**: Spending too much time learning theory or tools at the expense of building practical projects, which is essential for reinforcing learning.\n\n10. **Inconsistent Coding Practices**: Using different styles or practices throughout a codebase, leading to a lack of uniformity and increased difficulty in reading and maintaining code.\n\n11. **Neglecting Performance and Optimization**: Writing code that works but is inefficient, without understanding how to assess and improve performance.\n\n12. **Failure to Refactor**: Not revisiting or improving existing code after initial development, leading to technical debt over time.\n\n13. **Resisting Learning New Tools**: Becoming too attached to particular tools or languages without exploring alternatives that might offer better solutions.\n\n14. **Lack of Community Engagement**: Not participating in developer communities, which can limit networking opportunities and exposure to new ideas or practices.\n\n15. **Tunnel Vision**: Getting overly focused on a single project or technology stack, which can hinder broad technical understanding and adaptability.\n\nRecognizing and addressing these bad habits early can help self-taught programmers become well-rounded developers and improve their coding practices over time.",
